[ per plate ]
- 1 head broccoli (florets + peeled stem rounds)
- 1 apple, 5mm dice, skin on (Granny Smith ideal; Pink Lady / Braeburn also great)
- 2-3 spring onions, whites and greens separated
- rice vinegar, sesame oil, fresh ginger, chili flakes, salt

[ charred broccoli ]
1. Cut florets walnut-sized; peel stem with veg peeler, slice into 0.5cm rounds
2. Hot dry wok or pan, tiny oil — char in spots before adding any liquid
3. 1 tbsp water, lid on for 60-90 sec to steam through
4. Season: salt + small drizzle sesame oil

[ apple relish ]
1. Dice apple 5mm, skin on
2. Combine apple + spring onion greens with: generous splash rice vinegar, 0.5 tsp grated
   ginger, pinch salt, pinch chili flakes (or few drops sesame oil instead)
3. Rest 10 mins — the acid lightly pickles and transforms it from diced to relish

[ spring onion whites ]
- Thin diagonal slices
- Optional: soak in cold water 5 mins to crisp and tame the bite, then drain and pat dry

[ plating ]
- Charred broccoli on the plate
- Apple relish spooned over and around the pork specifically — it's doing a job on the fat,
  not the potatoes
- Spring onion whites scattered over everything at the end
- Designed as a supporting act: its job is to cut richness and provide freshness, not compete


---

[ why this combination ]
Rich fatty pork + fried starchy potato = the plate needs brightness, acidity, raw crunch, and
water content. Apple provides fruity sweetness and tart acidity that caramelised sugars can't
replicate. Broccoli brings vegetal freshness and char. Spring onion brings sharp aromatic bite
and color. Every element has a specific job on the plate, not just a third delicious thing.

Centuries of fruit-with-pork pairings (apple sauce, Cumberland sauce, quince) exist for good
reason: fruit acidity cuts rendered fat in a way that other acidities don't quite manage.

[ the broccoli technique ]
The char-then-steam approach gives you two things: blackened, slightly smoky exterior (flavor
depth, visual interest) and a still-crunchy interior. Same wok logic as stir-fried potatoes —
harmonises across the plate. Don't skip the charring phase; broccoli steamed without it tastes
like a different dish. The stem rounds are worth the effort — sweetest part of the plant and
they cook beautifully to a near-translucent slide.

[ the relish template ]
Raw crunchy fruit or veg + sharp allium + acid + small aromatic + brief rest.
Works anywhere you have a rich main: diced pear + red onion + sherry vinegar for duck;
pickled cucumber + shallot for fatty fish; pomegranate + mint + lemon for lamb. Once you think
in terms of what the plate is missing rather than what else sounds good, these suggest
themselves naturally.

[ apple variety ]
Tart (Granny Smith): ideal foil for rich pork. Sweet (Gala, Fuji): lean hard on the vinegar.
Pink Lady / Braeburn: sweet-tart balance, best of both. Keep skin on — the colour contrast
and slight texture against the fatty pork is part of what makes it land.
